      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <h1> Shepherd Internship Takes Cadet to the Bronx</h1>
       <div class="alignRight newsimagelarge">
        <img src="/uploadedImages/_VMI/Communications_Marketing/Newscenter/Headlines/Headline_Images/13-14/SamHudson2016KN0007Fulltext.jpg" alt="FullTextImage/img/@alt" class="bordered">
        <span class="caption">Sam Hudson '17</span>
       </div>
       <p>LEXINGTON, Va., Sept. 30, 2015 - Cadet Sam Hudson ’17 may be from a small town in Texas, but he has a big heart and it’s filled with big ideas for action. So spending the summer in New York City on a Shepherd internship allowed him to act and fueled him with more ideas. <br><br>The program, sponsored by the Shepherd Higher Education Consortium on Poverty, of which VMI is a member, sends cadets into impoverished areas of the country where they live on a small stipend for eight weeks and work within the community. Hudson lived on $14 a day in Brooklyn and commuted into the Bronx and mid-town Manhattan where he worked with high school students. <br><br>“A lot of my kids were refugees, a lot of my kids were immigrants, and it’s pulling them out of a mindset of, ‘Well, we have it better here than we do in our own country’ and putting them in the mindset of, ‘It doesn’t matter where you come from, you can still make it into the middle class,'’’ explained Hudson. <br><br>The students were learning computer programming, but Hudson focused on teaching them professional development:<br><br>“It was how to professionally network. How do you interact in an office environment? Things that high schoolers don’t necessarily get exposure to in the communities that we were serving.”<br><br>Normally, cadets must complete the Poverty and Human Capability course offered by Dr. Duncan Richter in the Department of English, Rhetoric, and Humanistic Studies. They then apply for the internship, interview with faculty, then interview with the Consortium.<br><br>But, as Maj. Dorothy Hayden of VMI career services explained, “This year we tried something different by opening the internship selection process to cadets who had not taken the course, but had an interest in serving in an impoverished community. Cadet Hudson was interviewed by a panel of faculty members and was competitively selected for the internship.”<br><br>Hudson, who is a psychology major, got the idea of applying for the internship from his academic adviser, Lt. Col. Keith Kline. “I love the idea of providing a service to the fellow man, like VMI the citizen-solider, … so this was an opportunity to scale that up a thousandfold,” Hudson said.<br><br>The Shepherd Program is just the beginning for Hudson. He plans to join the Peace Corps after graduation. And he would like to start his own non-profit, one that takes students out of the one-mile radius they have probably never left and puts them in leadership situations far from home. He believes solving poverty problems will not only benefit those afflicted by poverty, but the entire country. <br><br> “The single most untapped natural resource in our country is the impoverished. The skills, the ingenuity, the intelligence, all of these things that we have access to through a good school system, through good jobs – if we can take that and apply that to the impoverished, we could advance society in ways that we can’t even imagine in a very short amount of time.” <br><br>Hudson learned a great deal from his experience to say the least. But he believes the program benefited him a fraction of the amount it benefited the students he helped.<br><br>“One of the things I’m taking away more than anything is the idea that poverty is not necessarily about giving people on the street corner money or giving them education,” he said. “It’s about giving them an experience so they can educate themselves. I feel like that’s the solution to urban poverty.”<br><em><br>– Kelly Nye</em></p>
       <p><a target="_blank" title="Cabell Willis '14 reflects on his Shepherd experience" href="http://shepherdconsortium.org/finding-the-trajectory-the-service-for-which-i-am-fit/">Cabell Willis '14 reflects on his Shepherd experience</a></p>
       <p align="center">&nbsp;-VMI-</p> 
